–1530","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1453–Female":"1453–Deceased","1455–Female":"1455–Deceased","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","Cir 1427":"1427","Cir 1448":"1448","Cir 1447":"1447","Cir 1455":"1455","1450":"1450","Cir 1453":"1453","Cir 1450":"1450","1448":"1448","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1453":"1453","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1509":"1509","1427":"1427","Saxony, Germany":"Saxony, Germany","Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, Switzerland":"Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, Switzerland","Walthersdorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Walthersdorf, Annaberg, Kreis Annaberg, Saxony, Germany","Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, , Switzerland":"Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, Switzerland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Täuber","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Chaim, Hillel, Yitzchok, Aron, Elchonon, Ezriel, Moshe, Shachar, Shlomy, Aba, Ben Zion, Benzion.  German Kurt, Otto, Aloysius, Armin, Frieda, Ilse, Katharina, Konrad, Manfred, Uwe.","German (also <b>Täuber</b>): variant of   Taube   1 ‘pigeon, dove’. The <i>-er</i> inflection denotes the male bird, but in most cases this is an occupational name for a pigeon breeder, from an agent noun derivative ending in <i>-er(t)</i>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Taub   2, with the strong inflectional ending <i>-er</i>, originally used before a male personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Toberman","meanings":["Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Tauber   + Yiddish <i>man</i>‘man’."]},{"name":"Taube","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Gerhard, Gunter, Heinrich, Kurt, Otto, Wolfram.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from German <i>Taube</i> ‘pigeon, dove’ (Middle High German <i>tūbe</i>). The German name is either a metonymic occupational name for a keeper of doves or pigeons or a nickname for a mild and gentle person; the Jewish surname is artificial.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Toybe</i> (from Yiddish <i>toyb</i> ‘dove’)."]}]},{"name":"Ursula","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Ursula</i>, a diminutive of <i>ursa</i> ‘(she-)bear’. This was the name of a 4th-century saint martyred at Cologne with a number of companions, traditionally said to have been eleven thousand, but more probably just eleven, the exaggeration being due to a misreading of a diacritic mark in an early manuscript. This name was moderately popular in the 16th century, but its use in the English-speaking world today is selective. A more recent influence has been the film actress  Ursula Andress  (  b. 1936  in Switzerland)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ursula Täuber was born in 1427, in Saxony, Germany as the daughter of Hans Täuber and Veronika von Waldkirch. She married Burckhard Peyer gen von Thengen in 1447, in Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, Switzerland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 3 daughters."},"et":{"Cir 1427–":"1427–Surnud","1427–Female":"1427–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1425–1485":"1425–1485","1446–1530":"1446–1530","1448–1509":"1448–1509","1450–1530":"1450–1530","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1453–Female":"1453–Surnud","1455–Female":"1455–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","Cir 1427":"1427","Cir 1448":"1448","Cir 1447":"1447","Cir 1455":"1455","1450":"1450","Cir 1453":"1453","Cir 1450":"1450","1448":"1448","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1453":"1453","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1509":"1509","1427":"1427","Saxony, Germany":"Sachsen, Saksamaa","Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, Switzerland":"Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, Šveits","Walthersdorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Walthersdorf, Annaberg, Kreis Annaberg, Freistaat Sachsen, Saksamaa","Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, , Switzerland":"Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen, Šveits"},"fi":{"Cir 1427–":"1